Reports scope functions ('let', 'run', 'apply', 'also') that can be converted between each other. Using corresponding functions makes your code simpler. The quick-fix replaces the scope function to another one. Example: 'val x = "".let {
      it.length
  }' After the quick-fix is applied: 'val x = "".run {
      length
  }'

fullDescription.markdown:
Reports scope functions (`let`, `run`, `apply`, `also`) that can be converted between each other.

Using corresponding functions makes your code simpler.

The quick-fix replaces the scope function to another one.

**Example:**


      val x = "".let {
          it.length
      }

After the quick-fix is applied:


      val x = "".run {
          length
      }

fullDescription.text:
Reports an 'if' expression that checks variable being null or not right after initializing it that can be converted into an elvis operator in the initializer. Example: 'fun test(foo: Int?, bar: Int): Int {
      var i = foo
      if (i == null) {
          return bar
      }
      return i
  }' The quick-fix converts the 'if' expression with an initializer into an elvis expression: 'fun test(foo: Int?, bar: Int): Int {
      var i = foo ?: return bar
      return i
  }'

fullDescription.markdown:
Reports an `if` expression that checks variable being null or not right after initializing it that can be converted into an elvis operator in the initializer.

**Example:**


      fun test(foo: Int?, bar: Int): Int {
          var i = foo
          if (i == null) {
              return bar
          }
          return i
      }

The quick-fix converts the `if` expression with an initializer into an elvis expression:


      fun test(foo: Int?, bar: Int): Int {
          var i = foo ?: return bar
          return i
      }

