Reports binary expressions that consist of different operators without parentheses. Such expressions can be less readable due to different precedence rules of operators. Example:   fun foo(b: Boolean?, i: Int?) {
      val x = b ?: i == null // evaluated as `(b ?: i) == null`
      val y = i ?: 0 + 1 // evaluated as `i ?: (0 + 1)`
  }

Reports calls with an unused return value when the called function returns a lambda from an expression body. If there is '=' between function header and body block, code from the function will not be evaluated which can lead to incorrect behavior. Remove = token from function declaration can be used to amend the code automatically. Example: 'fun printHello() = { println("Hello") }

  fun main() {
      printHello() // This function doesn't print anything
  }' After the quick-fix is applied: 'fun printHello() { println("Hello") }

  fun main() {
      printHello()
  }'

